Or, perhaps a movie that looks at the valiant resistance of the Palestinian civilians to decades of illegal Israeli occupation and violence.  Or maybe a movie about the CIA's endless coups and assassinations carried out around the globe decade after decade after decade in service to Western capitalism. snippet.textDisplay:
Now lets talk about the Elephant in the room.
If this movie is supposed to be early 1942, then they got it wrong, as the first Fletcher class commissioned, the USS Nicholas, was commissioned 4th june 1942, and when you consider it takes a couple of months to do a work/shake down cruise to prepare the ship for full front line service, you would only see the first Fletchers in action in the last quarter of 1942, which actually happened, as they got heavily involved in the vicious night battles around Guadalcanal.
Fletchers was mostly employed in the Pacific, for several reasons.
One being the most modern and capable fleet destroyer, they where needed for the before mentioned vicious battles in the Pacific.
And although a Fletcher is very capable at escorting convoys against u-boats, like corvettes or sloops, the latter are hopeless for naval engagement, compared to the Fletchers.
Two, from a design perspective, they were better suited for operations in the calmer Pacific than the North Atlantic, as the forward part of the ship had an overall lower free board, compared to previous classes of US destroyers and their British counterpart.
The first Fletchers did not have 40mm AA guns let alone quad 40mm mounts.
The 1.1" quad "Chicago Organ" was the first medium AA mount used.
And it was the most common one in early/first half 1942 on US warships of destroyer size and upwards.
However from late 1942, Fletchers coming out of the shipyards, started to sport one or two, twin 40mm AA mounts and a handfull of 20mm's, due to the increading air threat.
But as the air threat in mid atlantic was very little during most of the battle of the Atlantic for obvious reasons, the majority of 40mm Bofors produced during the earlier stages of the war, was installed on warships destined for operations in the Pacific, or other places with higher enemy air activity.
And going into nit picking, the bridge structure is also incorrect, as that is of an later "squared" bridge type produced Fletchers, the early ones had a round bridge.
Early Radar sets did not have the PPI screens, but oscilloscope type screens, but hey the common viewer, better understand the former PPI type, than the latter.
When all things said, I do hope that it will spark an interest in younger generations, to read more on WW2 naval history and the various technical acheivements, that helped defeat the u-boat menace. 🤔🤔🤔
snippet.textOriginal:
Now lets talk about the Elephant in the room.
If this movie is supposed to be early 1942, then they got it wrong, as the first Fletcher class commissioned, the USS Nicholas, was commissioned 4th june 1942, and when you consider it takes a couple of months to do a work/shake down cruise to prepare the ship for full front line service, you would only see the first Fletchers in action in the last quarter of 1942, which actually happened, as they got heavily involved in the vicious night battles around Guadalcanal.
Fletchers was mostly employed in the Pacific, for several reasons.
One being the most modern and capable fleet destroyer, they where needed for the before mentioned vicious battles in the Pacific.
And although a Fletcher is very capable  at escorting convoys against u-boats, like corvettes or sloops, the latter are hopeless for naval engagement, compared to the Fletchers.
Two, from a design perspective, they were better suited for operations in the calmer Pacific than the North Atlantic, as the forward part of the ship had an overall lower free board, compared to previous classes of US destroyers and their British counterpart.
The first Fletchers did not have 40mm AA guns let alone quad 40mm mounts.
The 1.1" quad "Chicago Organ" was the first medium AA mount used.
And it was the most common one in early/first half 1942 on US warships of destroyer size and upwards.
However from late 1942, Fletchers coming out of the shipyards, started to sport one or two, twin 40mm AA mounts and a handfull of 20mm's, due to the increading air threat.
But as the air threat in mid atlantic was very little during most of the battle of the Atlantic for obvious reasons, the majority of 40mm Bofors produced during the earlier stages of the war, was installed on warships destined for operations in the Pacific, or other places with higher enemy air activity.
And going into nit picking, the bridge structure is also incorrect, as that is of an later "squared" bridge type produced Fletchers, the early ones had a round bridge.
Early Radar sets did not have the PPI screens, but oscilloscope type screens, but hey the common viewer, better understand the former PPI type, than the latter.
When all things said, I do hope that it will spark an interest in younger generations, to read more on WW2 naval history and the various technical acheivements, that helped defeat the u-boat menace.  🤔🤔🤔
